'''Bishop Joseph Colgan''', DD,  was an Irish born [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Madras and Mylapore|Roman Catholic Archbishop of Madras]], India. 
Born on April 1, 1824 in Donore, County Westmeath, he studied in Navan, and for the priesthood in [[Maynooth College]]. Ordained in 1846 in 1847 he moved to India, where he served as a School principal, and Army Chaplin and priest in the Madras Vicarate.<ref>[http://newspapers.bc.edu/cgi-bin/bostonsh?a=d&d=BOSTONSH19110304-01.2.5 Obituary] The Sacred Heart Review, Volume 45, Number 11, 4 March 1911, Boston College.</ref>
Dr. Colgan was honoured becoming a Fellow of Madras University.<ref>[https://books.google.ie/books?id=Y8AKI2nqPBQC&pg=PA88&lpg=PA88&dq=Bishop+Colgan+Madras&source=bl&ots=JTB6g1cV29&sig=qVM1TU3fC8T0t0MVWz_U7WF86YY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1gcmawqfMAhVCWhoKHUoaBHI4ChDoAQgoMAM#v=onepage&q=Bishop%20Colgan%20Madras&f=false  Most Rev. Dr. Joseph Colgan DD] Dictionary of Indian Biography</ref>
Dr. Colgan was appointed Bishop of Madras in 1882 succeeding Bishop Stephen Fennelly and became the first Archbishop of Madras in 1886,<ref>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/madr0.htm Bishop of Madras] www.gcatholic.org</ref> he served as archbishop until he died on February 13, 1911.

