{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}} '''Satnam''' ([[Gurmukhi]]:ਸਤਿ ਨਾਮੁ ) is the main word that appears in the [[Sikh]] sacred [[scripture]] called the [[Guru Granth Sahib]]. It is part of the [[Gurbani]] [[Shabda|shabad]] called [[Mool Mantra]] which is repeated daily by all Sikhs. This word succeeds the word "[[Ik Onkar|Ek-onkar]]" which means "There is only one constant" or commonly "There is one God". The words ''[[Satya|sat]]'' means "true/everlasting" and ''[[Nāma|nam]]'' means "name".<ref>{{cite book|last=Kaur Rait|first=Satwant|title=Sikh Women in England: Religious,Social and Cultural Beliefs [Paperback]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hRfkTq1ykSIC&pg=PA20|accessdate=11 November 2010|date=31 Jan 2005|publisher=Trentham Books Ltd; illustrated edition |isbn=1-85856-353-4|page=20|chapter=Chapter 2}}</ref> In this instance, this would mean, "whose name is truth".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Nijhawan|first1=Michael|last2=Mandair |first2=Arvind|title=Shared idioms, sacred symbols, and the articulation of identities in South Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tbOLCZlymxYC&pg=PA66|accessdate=11 November 2010|date=20 Feb 2009|publisher=Routledge; 1st edition|isbn=0-415-95828-8 |page=66|chapter=2 The Politics of Non-duality: Unraveling the Hermeneutics of Modern Sikh Theology}}</ref> Satnam is referred to God as the Name of God is True and Everlasting.<ref>[http://www.realsikhism.com/index.php?action=gmeaning&glossaryid=64&glossaryterm=Satnam Real Sikhism: Meaning of Term Satnam]</ref>
The word ''nam'' in Sikhism has two meanings. "It meant both an application and a symbol of the All-pervading Supreme Reality that sustained the universe. [[Guru Nanak]] in his teachings emphasized the need of repeating Sat-Nam to realize the All-pervading Supreme Reality."<ref>{{cite book|last=Singh Dhillon|first=Dalbir|title=Sikhism Origin and Development|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=osnkLKPMWykC&pg=PA226|accessdate=12 November 2010|year=1988|publisher=Atlantic Publishers and Distributors|isbn= |page=226|chapter=3 Evolution of Institutions and Ethical Doctrines}}</ref>
